DIV2.P:
Sir Philip Sydney 3. when hee had ex∣pressed the heauie departure of Dorus from his friend Pirocles, endeth thus; 
So much his owne heart did finde him faul∣tie, to vnbend anie way the continuall vse of their deare friendship.
5. When he had manifested the incon∣stancie of the people, and setled perseue∣rance of Philanax & Euarchus, he addeth; 
So euil ballanced be the extremities of po∣pular mindes, and so much naturall impe∣riousnes there rests in a wel framed spirit.
